Explanation:

The problem requires finding the minimum number of swaps needed to make the string balanced. We can solve this problem by iterating through the string once and counting the number of swaps needed. If the characters at adjacent positions are not matching, we increment the swaps variable. Since the string has an even length, we can iterate from the first character to the middle character (n/2) and then from the last character to the second-to-last character (n/2 - 1). This ensures that we cover all pairs of matching brackets. The time complexity is O(n), where n is the length of the string. The space complexity is O(1) since we only use a constant amount of space for the swaps variable. The energy implications are low since the algorithm only performs a constant number of operations.

